column168: DRIVER DISPATCHED ON APRIL 7, 1995, THE FIBERGATE CORP. PLANT IN STEPHENVILLE, TX., TO TRANSPORT A LOADED 40 FT. IM CONTAINER TO BARBOUR'S CUT TERMINAL, PORT OF HOUSTON.  LADING CONSISTED OF 8 DRUMS CUMENE HYDROPEROXIDE ALONG WITH PALLETIZED NON-HAZARDOUS CARGO.  DRIVER LEFT SHIPPER'S LOCATION AT 4:15 PM AND TRANSPORTED THE LOAD TO THE PALLETIZED YARD IN HOUSTON FOR DELIVERY ON MONDAY, APRIL 10.  DRIVER STATES THAT HE NOTICED NO LEAKAGE FROM THE CONTAINER WHEN HE PERFORMED THIS POST TRIP INSPECTION AT 11:30 PM.  AFTER SATURDAY MORNING SAFETY MEETING, THE DRIVER, AN OWNER OPERATOR, WAS PREPARING TO PERFORM SOME P.M. ON HIS TRACTOR WHEN HE NOTED THAT LIQUID WAS LEAKING FROM THE CONTAINER.  HE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THE UNDERSIGNED.  THE TIME WAS 11:30 AM.  AFTER CONSULTING THE MSDS, THE CONTAINER WAS RELOCATED TO A REMOTE AREA OF THE YARD AND ABSORBENT APPLIED TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE.  ABSORBENT WAS APPLIED TO THE SPILLED MATERIAL AT THE FIRST LOCATION.  CALLS WERE MADE TO BOTH THE SHIPPER'S AND MANUFACTURER'S EMERGENCY NUMBERS.  THE HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM WAS SUMMONED BEFORE THE CONTAINER WAS UNSEALED AND OPENED.  ABSORBENT WAS APPLIED TO SPILLAGE ON THE CONTAINER FLOOR AND THE CONTAINER WAS THEN MOVED TO OUR DOCK WHERE IT WAS UNLOADED.  TWO 55 GAL. STEEL BARRELS WERE DAMAGED; ONE WAS LEAKING. THE LEAKER WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  ALL LADING AND THE CONTAINER WERE DECONTAMINATED ACCORDING TO THE CHEMICAL MANUFACTURER'S INSTRUCTIONS.  EXAMINATION OF THE DAMAGED TO THE DRUMS INDICATE FORKLIFT DAMAGE.

DOCKMAN LOADED DRUMS ON TRAILER PW617.  HE DID NOT PUT BARRIER OF DUNNAGE UP IN FRONT OF DRUMS.  HE THEN STARTED TO LOAD A PALLET BEHIND THE DRUMS. THE PALLET WAS NOT A 4-WAY AND FORKS WERE PROTRUDING OUT FROM THE REAR OF THE PALLET.  ONE FORK PUNCTURED THE DRUM AND CONTENTS BEGAN SPILLING OUT IMMEDIATELY. OTHER FREIGHT WAS MOVED AWAY FROM THE DRUM AS QUICKLY AS POSSIBLE AND CLEAN-UP BEGAN.  HE SHOULD HAVE PUT UP A BARRIER, EMPTY PALLETS, OR DUNNAGE DEHIND THE DRUMS AND HE SHOULD ALSO HAVE BEEN AWARE OF THE SHORT PALLET HE WAS LOADING.  HE REALIZED HIS ERROR IMMEDIATELY, BROUGHT IT TO THE SUPERVISOR'S ATTENTION.  ANOTHER DOCKMAN HELPING WITH CLEAN-UP COMPLAINED OF HEADACHE.  HE SAID HE HAD A HEADACHE WHEN HE CAME TO WORK THAT DAY-DID NOT GO TO THE DOCTOR.

THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED ON THE TOPS OF THE CONTAINERS AND DID NOT ESCAPE TO THE ENVIRONMENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND REPLACED THE DEFECTIVE BUNG CAPS. ALL SPILL DEBRIS WAS CONTAINERIZED AND DISPOSED OF AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

ON APRIL 4 AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30 PM (MST) CALGON COMPLETED LOADING OUR TRAILER.  TOM JENKINS, OUR DRIVER, CHECKED THE LOAD AT THAT TIME AND FOUND NO LEAKS.  DURING TRANSIT, HE CHECKED HIS LOAD SEVERAL TIMES.  WHEN HE STOPPED TO SLEEP, HE CHECKED THE LOAD AND AGAIN BEFORE HE STARTED DRIVING. ON APRIL 5TH, AS HE WAS COMING DOWN LOOKOUT PASS, ANOTHER TRUCK RADIOED HIM, SAYING THERE WAS LIQUID DRIPPING FROM UNDER HIS TRAILER.  AFTER CHECKING HIS MSDS'S AND SHIPPING PATERS, HE RADIOED THE HAUGEN SCALE FOR HELP.  THE SCALE APPARENTLY NOTIFIED THE HIGHWAY DEPARTMENT AND A SHERIFF ARRIVED AT THE SCENE.  WATKINS AND SHEPARD WAS NOTIFIED BY THE MISSOULA HIGHWAY DEPARTMENT OF THE SPILL ABOUT 1:30 PM (MST).  A FIRE DEPARTMENT AND SHERIFF HAD THE TRUCK MOVED INTO THE REST AREA.  THE UNITS WERE PARKED ON A DOWNWARD SLOPING ASPHALT LOT.  A CURB, SAND, DELIVERED BY A SAND TRUCK AND FLOOR DRY WAS USED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL UNTIL THE HAZMAT TEAMS ARRIVED.  THE MISSOULA RURAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AGREED TO GO TO THE SCENE TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.  WE HAD A WATKINS SHEPARD DRIVER PICK UP A TOTE FROM STONE CONTAINER TO BRING TO THE SCENE HOPING TO TRANSFER THE LIQUID FROM THE LEAKING TOTE TO THE NEW ONE.  THE MISSOULA RURAL FIRE DEPARTMENT DETERMINED THE SPILL WAS LARGER THAN ORIGINALLY THOUGHT AND REQUIRED ADDITIONAL HELP.  ROAR ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE FROM SPOKANE WA. WAS CALLED TO HELP WITH CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN UP.  AFTER DETERMINING WHAT TOTE WAS LEAKING, MISSOULA RURAL FIRE DEPARTMENT CLOSED AND SECURED THE VALVE, STOPPING THE LEAK.  THE VALVE ON THE TOTE WAS NOT FULLY CLOSED AND DID NOT HAVE THE SAFETY CAP LATCHED DOWN OVER THE VALVE.  THIS ALLOWED LIQUID TO LEAK OUT.  THE LIQUID THAT WAS ON THE GROUND AND IN THE TRAILER WAS PUMPED INTO THE EXTRA TOTE.  ROAR CLEANED UP THE SAND AND LIQUID AND PLACED IT IN BARRELS, THEY CURRENTLY HAVE THE BARRELS AND WILL DISPOSE OF THEM.  A NEUTRALIZING AGENT WAS SPRAYED ON THE ASPHALT, THE TRAILER AND TRACTOR DURING THE CLEANUP.  WHEN THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WAS RELEASED, THE DRIVER DELIVERED THE LOAD TO STONE AND RETURNED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO OUR FACILITY IN MISSOULA WHERE THEY WERE THOROUGHLY CLEANED.  BOTH TOM WALTER AND MYSELF TALKED TO ED NEHAUS OF CALGON ABOUT THE CONDITION OF THE TOTE AND VALVE AND QUESTIONED WHY THE VALVE WAS NOT PROPERLY CLOSED AND SECURED.  HE ASSURED US THAT THEY WOULD BE DOING A THOROUGH INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE WHAT OCCURRED.

ON APRIL 3, 1995, JP4 JET FUEL WAS BEING TRANSPORTED IN A 500 GALLON CARGO TANK FROM THE SALT RIVER PROJECT'S (SRP) EAST VALLEY FACILITY TO THE INTERSECTION OF FOREST ROUTE 512 AND FOREST ROUTE 291, APPROXIMATELY THREE MILES SOUTH OF STATE HIGHWAY 260. AROUND 1300 THE JP4 JET FUEL STARTING LEAKING FROM THE CARGO TANK DUE TO A STRESS FRACTURE ASSOCIATED WITH ONE OF THE SEAMS LOCATED AT OR NEAR THE BOTTOM PORTION OF THE TANK. APPROXIMATELY 60 GALLONS OF AVIATION FUEL SPILLED FROM THE CARGO TANK. THE JP4 JET FUEL IS USED BY SRP FLIGHT OPERATIONS TO FUEL THE COMPANY HELICOPTER AT THE VARIOUS LOCATIONS WHILE PERFORMING WORK. THE INCIDENT OCCURRED ON A ROUGH RURAL ROAD. IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE CONDITION OF THE ROAD CAUSED THE STRESS FRACTURE IN THE CARGO TANK. ACTIONS TAKEN AT THE TIME OF DISCOVERY INCLUDE DISPERSING THE LEAK OVER THE ROAD FOR APPROXIMATELY FOUR MILES TO KEEP FROM COMPILING A CENCENTRATION OF FUEL UNTIL THE CREW COULD ARRANGE TO OFF LOAD THE REMAINING FUEL, THUS MINIMIZING ANY POTENTIAL IMPACT ON THE ENVIRONMENT. AT THE FIRST AVAILABLE LOCATION WHERE A HELICOPTER COULD LAND, THE FUEL WAS UNLOADED DIRECTLY INTO SRP'S HELICOPETER. AT THE LOCATIONS WERE THE FUEL HAD SPILLED ON THE GROUND, SRP REMOVED THE SOIL AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF THE SOIL UNDER ALL LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL EPA GUIDELINES. ALL NECESSARY EPA NOTIFICATIONS FOR SPILL RESPONSE WERE COMPLETED. PREVENTIVE ACTIONS IN THE FUTURE INCLUDE KEEPING PLUG-N-DIKE ON THE CARGO TANK. PLUG-N-DIKE IS A GREY PUTTY SUBSTANCE THAT WILL STOP A STRESS FRACTURE OR SMALL PUNCTURE IN A FUEL TANK WHILE IT IS LEAKING. PLUG-N-DIKE WILL BE USED TO STOP THE LEAK IMMEDIATELY UPON DISCOVERY. IN ADDITION, ABSORBENT BOOMS WILL BE CARRIED ON THE CARGO TANK AND USED TO CONTAIN THE POOLED SPILL.

ON APRIL 21, 1995, VEHICLE #1 WAS PROCEEDING NORTH BOUND ON I-75.  UNIT #1 WAS STOPPED AT FORT WRIGHT, KY POLICE DEPARTMENT AND WAS ADVISED THAT SOMEONE HAD REPORTED TO THE FORT WRIGHT POLICE DEPARTMENT THAT A TAILER IN FRONT OF THEM AS EMITTING A STRONG ODOR.  ARGO TANK 1085 WAS CHECKED AT THIS TIME AND A SMALL LEAK WAS DISCOVERED IN FRONT OF THE SUMP IN A WELDED SEAM AREA.  A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE CARGO TANK CATCHING THE LEAKING MATERIALS.  THE UNIT WAS STOPPED AT 2008 ON 4.21.95.  I-75, BOTH NORTH AND SOUTH BOUNDS WAS CLOSED UNTIL 0300 ON 4/22/95.  I-75 WAS CLOSED BY THE CHEIF OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT F COVINGTON OR KENTON COUNTY, ALONG WITH A KENTON COUNTY INDIVIDUAL.  AT APPROXIMATELY 2135, THERE WAS A CLEAN TRAILER SENT TO THE SCENE TO TRANSFER THE LOAD.  THE LOAD COULD HAVE BEEN OFF LOADED IN APROXIMATELY 1 TO 1 1/2 HOURS.  HOWEVER, DUE TO COMPLICATION AT THE SECNE WITH ALL OF THE DIFFERENT FIRE DEPARTMENTS, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONSE UNITS AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS THE SCENE WAS NOT CLEARED UNTIL APPROXIMATELY 0300 ON 4/22/95.  COMPANY UNIT 1085 HAD RECEIVED ITS FEDERAL ANNUAL SAFETY INSPECTION, EXTERNAL VISUAL INSPECTION, INTERNAL VIDSUAL INSPECTION, LEAKAGE TEST AND THICKNESS TEST ON FEBRUARY 6, 1995. IT HAD ALSO RECEIVED THE COMPANY 90 DAY INSPECTION AND MAINTENANCE ON FEBRUARY 3, 1995.

MR PAYNE, TRAINMASTER NOTIFIED HAZMAT.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND THE CONSIGNEE CONTAVTED MURTA. THE CONSIGNEE DISPATCHED AN IN-HOSE RESPONSE TEAM TO MAKE ANY NECASSARY REPAIRS TO THE CAR. CSX INTERMODEL, FOUND A LEAKING INTERMODAL TANK AT THE RAMP IN JACKSONVILLE, FL. TANK WAS ISOLATED, SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  ENVIRONMENTAL RECOVERY GROUP (REG) RESPONDED BUT FOUND PRODUCT RESIDUE IN THE OVERFLOW BASIN GROUND THE FILL HOLE ON TOP.  ALL 8 FASTENERS ON THE FILL HOLE COVER WERE LOSE ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SPILL INTO THE OVERFLOW BASIN AND THEN THROUGH THE DRAIN PIPE.  ERG CLEANED UP THE RESIDUE, TIGHTENED DOWN THE FILL HOLE COVER THEN HAD THE TANK MOVED TO CONFIRM IT WAS SECURE.  TANK WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

WASTE NITRIC AND HYDROFLOURIC ACID (HAZARDOUS WASTE NO. K062) WAS BEING TRANSPORTED FROM THE JESSOP STEEL COMPANY., WASHINGTON PA. PLANT TO THE MILL SERVICE, INC. (MSI) YUKON PLANT ON APRIL 17, 1995.  WHILE ENROUTE TO THE YUKON PLANT, THE DRIVER STOPPED AT RT519 TRUCK STOP FOR LUNCH APPROXIMATELY 14:50.  THE DRIVER SPOTTED A WET SPOT ON FRONT OF TRAILER, WASTE ACID WAS SEEPING FROM RIGHT TOP FRONT OF TRAILER.  THE DRIVER THEN DEPLOYED HAZ-MAT ABSORBANT SOCKS AND PILLOWS TO TRAILER FRAME RAIL AND ON BLACKTOP PARKING LOT.  HE THEN CALLED MSI DISPATCH TO REPORT HIS INCIDENT. MSI DISPATCHED A SPILL RESPONSE TEAM FROM THE YUKON PLANT.  ALONG WITH AND EMPTY TANKER.  THE SPILL RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED AT SPILL SITE APPROXIMATELY 15:75.  AT THAT TIME THEY SET UP A PUMP AND BEGIN PUMPING INTO THE EMPTY TANKER.  THE SPILLED WASTE WAS ABSORBED AND THE ROAD SURFACE CLEANED.  THE SPILL DID NOT LEAVE THE ROAD SURFACE.  THE ORIGINAL LADING AND THE SPILLED RESIDUES WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE YUKON PLANT FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. MSI OPERATED A HAZARDOUS WASTE TREATMENT FACILITY AN ASSOCIATED WASTE DISPOSAL UNIT AT THE YUKON PLANT UNDER THE AUTHORITY OF THE US ENVIRONMENTAL RESOURCES NO HEALTH RISJS WERE ASSOCIATED WITH THE SPILL AND NO EVACUATION WAS REQUIRED.  GEORGE SABOCHECK WITH THE PENNSYLVANIA D.E.R. ARRIVED AS INCIDENT WAS BEING CLEANED UP.  HE FILLED OUT AN INCIDENT REPORT.  AND REMAINED AT SITE UNTIL CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED APPROXIMATELY TIME 17:00.  THE TANK TRAILER WAS TESTED FOR EXTERNAL VISUAL, INTERNAL VISUAL. LINING INSPECTION, LEAKAGE TEST.  10-17-94. AND PRESSURE RETESTED 11-93.

FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED ALL FREE LUQIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND REPLACED THE EXISTING BUNG CAP FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORT TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT. EMPLOYEES FROM OUR INDUSTRIAL NEIGHBORS (SMUCKERS) SMELLED AN AMMONIA ODOR AND NOTIFIED THE POLICE.  POLICE CONTACTED THE FIRE DEPT. AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO OUR FACILITY AND TO SMUCKERS.  OUR LOCAL EMERGENCY CONTACT PERSONNEL WERE ALSO DISPATCHED TO OUR FACILITY.  A VALVE ON A SIGHT GLASS FOR AN ABSORBER STORAGE TANK WAS LEAKING VAPOR.  OUR PERSONNEL SHUT OFF THE VALVE AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  HAZMAT WAS NOT NOTIFIED FOR RESPONSE BECAUSE IT WAS DEEMED NOT NECESSARY.  FIRE DEPARTMENT TOOK PPM READINGS FOR AMMONIA.  AT THE LEAK SOURCE THE READING WAS 100 PPM AND 30 PPM FOR THE SURROUNDING AREA.  ONCE THE VALVE WAS SHUT OFF THE PPM VAVLUES DROPPED.  OUR AMMONIA SENSORS(SET TO TRIGGER AT 50 PPM) DID NOT GO OFF. SMUCKERS FACILITY WAS EVACUATED FOR ABOUT 45 MINUTES.  ONE(1) SMUCKERS EMPLOYEE REQUESTED TRANSPORT TO THE HOSPITAL.  LEAK WAS VAPOR ONLY AND TO THE ATMOSPHERE.  AFTER THE INCIDENT OUR EMPLOYEES THOROUGHLY INSPECTED OUR FACILITY AND A MINOR LEAK ON AN INCOMING RAIL CAR WAS DISCOVERED ON THE A END LIQUID VALVE OF THE RAIL CAR.  THE CAR WAS UNTAPPED AND BEING STORED ON AN ADJACENT RAIL SPUR AT OUR LOCATION.  OUR PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY OFF-LOADED THE CAR INTO OUR STORAGE TANKS.  THE CAR WAS DE-PRESSURIZED AND THE VALVE TAGGED.  THIS LEAK WAS VAPOR ONLY AND TO THE ATMOSPHERE.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY RUN IN MICHIGAN WHEN IN EARLY A.M. 4/26/95 HIS TAILGATE FAILED AND WOULD NOT COME DOWN. HE STOPPED AT FABCO EQUIPMENT INC IN MARQUETTE MI TO GET THE TAILGATE FIXED. FABCO WAS NOT ABLE TO REPAIR THE GATE BUT ARRANGED FOR A GARAGE 3 MILES DOWN THE ROAD TO LOOK AT IT. AT THIS TIME THE MECHANIC AND OUR DRIVER DID NOTICE A DRIPPING OF CHEMICAL FROM THE TRAILER WHICH OUR DRIVER DETERMINED WAS BLEACH (10% SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION). OF COURSE, OUR DRIVER SHOULD HAVE DEALT WITH THE PROBLEM AT THIS TIME BUT BECAUSE THE TAILGATE WAS STUCK IN THE UP POSITION IT WAS DIFFICULT TO GET INTO THE VAN, SO HE PROCEEDED TO THE LOCATION OF THE GARAGE, SOULLIERES MARATHON STATION. HE WAS PULLED OVER BY A PATROL CAR AS HE ENTERED THE STATION PROPERTY. SOMEONE HAD REPORTED THAT WE HAD A CHEMICAL LEAK, OBVIOUSLY SOMEONE FROM FABCO EQUIPMENT AS THERE WAS NOT ENOUGH OF A LEAK TO BE NOTICEABLE. THE OFFICER NOTED THAT THERE WERE A NUMBER OF HAZARDOUS CHEMICALS ON THE TRUCK AND IN SHORT ORDER OUR DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE SITUATION, AS POLICE, FIRE DEPT AND EMERGENCY GOVERNMENT PERSONAL TOOK OVER, WOULD NOT LET HIM OR ANYONE GET WITHIN 500 FEET OF THE TRUCK. THEY BECAME OVERLY CONCERNED AS OTHER HAZARDOUS CHEMICALS WERE ALSO ON THE TRUCK AT THE TIME. THESE INCLUDED 4 150# CYLINDERS OF SULFUR DIOXIDE GAS, 172 GALLONS OF MURIATIC ACID, 1070 GALLONS OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION (10%), 189 GALLONS OF TETRACHLOROETHYLENE, 750# OF CAUSTIC SODA BEADS, 50# OF BROMITE TABLETS, 5 GALLONS OF A CORROSIVE ACID CLEANER, AND ONE GALLON OF HYDROGEN PEROXIDE. OUR DRIVER TOLD THEM THAT IT WAS BLEACH THAT WAS LEAKING AND THAT HE COULD CORRECT THE PROBLEM WITHIN MINUTES. OUR DRIVER DID HAVE EMERGENCY RESPONSE SUPPLIES ON A CONTAINER BEHIND HIS TRACTOR WHICH ALSO CONTAINED A RESPIRATOR. HOWEVER, OUR DRIVER WAS NOT ALLOWED TO HANDLE THE PROBLEM AND WAS FORCED TO STAY 500 FEET FROM THE TRAILER. OUR HOME OFFICE WAS CALLED BY SOMEONE FROM THE SCENE, AND JIM CHERWINKA, PRESIDENT, GOT THE CALL. JIM WAS TOLD THAT FUMES WERE COMING FROM THE TRUCK AND THAT HAZMAT PERSONNEL WERE ON THE WAY. SOMETIME LATER JIM RECEIVED ANOTHER CALL AND WAS TOLD THAT THERE WAS NO HAZMAT TEAM AND THAT WE WOULD HAVE TO SOLVE THE PROBLEM. A 5 GALLON PLASTIC CARBOY WAS PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON OPEN TOP DRUM TO CONTAIN THE LEAK. TOTAL LEAKAGE WAS ESTIMATED AT LESS THAN A GALLON. ON MONDAY, MAY 1ST, I OPENED THE 55 GALLON DRUM AND WEIGHED THE LEAKY 5 GALLON CARBOY AT 44.5 LBS. ORIGINAL WEIGHT IS 52 LBS. THE 10% BLEACH WEIGHTS 10 LB/GAL SO TOTAL LOSS EVEN 5 DAYS LATER WAS ONLY ABOUT 3 QUARTS. LEAK SITE LOSS WAS PROBABLY LESS THAN A QUART AND CERTAINLY LESS THAN TWO QUARTS. column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE RECEIVER TO FIND ONE PAIL LEAKING. THE PAIL WAS OFF-LOADED AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED FROM THE TRAILER. CAUSE OF THE SPILL APPEARED TO BE FROM A NAIL IN ONE OF THE PALLETS HAD PUNCTURED THE PAIL AT THE BOTTOM. ALL WASTE WAS ACCEPTED BY THE RECEIVER FOR DISPOSAL.

CONTAINER HJCU 861073 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING AT THE CICERO RAMP IN CICERO, IL. INSPECTION OF THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER REVEALED TWO 55 GALLON DRUMS OF RESIN SOLUTION, 3 UN1866, WERE PUNCTURED NEAR THE TOP. THE PUNCTURE RESULTED IN APPROXIMATELY 0.5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT BEING RELEASED. THE DRUMS WERE REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER. THE CAUSE OF THE PUNCTURED DRUMS WERE DETERMINED TO BE IMPROPER LOADING.

TANK CAR GATX 21198 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING BY A CAR MAN AT APPROXIMATELY 1530 DURING ROUTINE INSPECTION OF A YARD TRACK IN GLENDIVE YARD. LEAK WAS REPORTED TO BN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONDER. INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THAT THE LEAK WAS APPROXIMATELY 3 TO 4 DRIPS A MINUTE FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE. THE PRODUCT ON THE GROUND EVAPORTATED RAPIDLY. AFTER BREAKING THE SHIPPER'S SEALS, THE TOP OPERATED BUTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS SECURELY CLOSED, STOPPING THE DRIPPING AFTER APPROXIMATELY TWO MINUTES. THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE STEM WAS TIGHTENED AND THE CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

WHILE IN THE RAIL YARD AT GOLDEN, COLORADO, TANK CAR ECUX 102211 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE. AFTER NOTIFICATION, THE CONSIGNEE RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THE LEAK COULD NOT BE STOPPED. ACTION WAS TAKEN TO CONTAIN THE LEAKAGE AND THE CAR WAS MOVED TO THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY FOR UNLOADING.

column168: UNIT #1 WAS EXITING NORTHBOUND I-271 TO CHAGRIN BLVD. WESTBOUND. UNIT #1 WAS IN THE LEFT LANE OF THE EXIT RAMP ATTEMPTING TO TURN LEFT ON TO CHAGRIN BLVD. WESTBOUND CENTER LANE. THE DRIVER STATED THAT HE FELT HIS LOAD "START TO GO" AS HE WAS MAKING THE LEFT TURN. UNIT #1 WHILE MAKING THE TURN, ROLLED OVER ON TO ITS RIGHT SIDE AND THEN CAME TO A STOP. AS A RESULT OF UNIT #1 ROLLING ON TO ITS SIDE, THE TANKER TRAILER WAS DAMAGED IN AT LEAST THREE LOCATIONS, ALLOWING GASOLINE FROM THE TANK TO ESCAPE ON TO THE ROADWAY. THE FINAL POINT OF REST OF UNIT 31 WAS ENTIRELY IN THE WESTBOUND CURB LANE OF CHAGRIN BLVD. ROADWAY, WITH THE FRONT OF UNIT #1 FACING IN A WESTERLY DIRECTION.

WHEN UNLOADING TRAILER AT DOCK, WORKER NOTICED PAIL ON TOP OF SKID HAD BEEN DAMAGED AND CONTACTED OS&D DEPARTMENT TO INSPECT. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT SEAM WAS STARTING TO SEEP SLIGHT AMOUNT OF CHEMICAL. REMOVED DAMAGED PAIL TO VENTILATED AREA AND CALLED EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO RECOUP AND RETURN PRODUCT TO SHIPPER. APPARENT CAUSE OF DAMAGE WAS FREIGHT BEING SET ON TOP OF SKID CAUSING DAMAGE TO PAIL.

ON MARCH 30, 1995 AT APPROXIMATELY 0300 HOURS, A CF EMPLOYEE NOTICED A CARTON WITH "HARMFUL KEEP AWAY FROM FOOD STUFFS" LABEL THAT APPEARED TO HAVE WATER MARKS ON THE BOX. THE EMPLOYEE NOTIFIED THE FREIGHT OPERATIONS MANAGER WHO ISOLATED THE AREA AND IDENTIFIED THE SHIPMEMT THAT APPEARED TO HAVE LEAKED. AS PRO 724022784. THE CARTON WAS 45 LBS., POISONOUS LIQUID NOS 6.1, UN2810. HE THEN MOVED IN CLOSER TO THE CARTON AND DISCOVERED THAT THE MARKS ON THE SIDE APPEARED TO BE DRY, THE CARTON WAS MOVED TO AN ISOLATED AREA TO BE HELD FOR DISPOSITION. THERE WAS NO DAMPNESS ON THE CARDBOARD UNDER THE CARTON, BUT THE PIECE THAT WAS DIRECTLY BELOW THE LEAKING CARTON WAS KEPT TO BE DISPOSED OF WITH THE LEAKING CONTAINER. THE LEAKING CONTAINER INSIDE THE BOX WAS A METAL 1 GALLON CAN, THE CAN HAS A PIN HOLE IN IT THAT APPEARS TO LEAK WITH THE CONTAINER IS MOVED. THERE IS NO DAMAGE TO THE OUTER CONTAINER.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE OCCURED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING HANDLED WITH A FORKLIFT BECAUSE OF ITS SIZE AND BULK.  DURING HANDLING THE SHIPMENT TURNED OVER AND WHEN THIS HAPPENED ODORS AND EVIDENCE OF A LEAKING MATERIAL WAS NOTICED IMMEDIATELY.  THE SHIPMENT WAS RIGHTED ISOLATED AND OPENED TO REVEAL SOME TYPE OF GASOLINE POWERED COMPRESSOR OR PUMP.  THE GAS TANK HAD NOT BEEN COMPLETELY PURGED OF FUEL AND THIS IS WHAT CAUSED THE SPILLAGE.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ACCORDING TO PROCEDURE.  THERE WERE NO CONTAINED ACCORDING TO PROCEDURE.  THERE WAS NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WARNING LABELS, MARKINGS NOR WAS THERE EVIDENCE OF A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ASSOCIATED WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD PENDING NOTIFIATION OF F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION.

DURING THE SORT OPERATIONS, WHEN THIS CONTAINER WAS MOVES, A WET RING OF LIQUID WAS OBSERVED UNDER THE CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS THEN PLACED INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM SO THEY COULD INSPECT THE CONTAINER CLOSER.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: DURING PM SORT OPERATIONS, STRONG AMMONIA FUMES BECAME EVIDENT IN THE WHSE.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT THIS UNMARKED, UNLABELED BOX WAS THE SOURCE OF THE ODORS.  THE BOX WAS THEN WET ON THE SIDE AND BOTTOM. THE SPILL CLEAN UP PERSON SUITED UP (FEDEX SPILL CLEAN UP EMPLOYEE) AND OPENED THE BOX.   INSIDE WAS A JUG THAT WAS INSIDE THE PACKAGE ON IT'S SIDE (CLOSURE SIDEWAYS).  THE SIDE OF THE JUG SAID "AMMONIUM HYDROXIDE". THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED WHO WENT TO THEIR OFFICE AND OBTAINED A MSDS AND BROUGHT IT TO THE TERMINAL. A FEDEX EMPLOYEE COMPLAINED OF NAUSEA AND HEADACHE AND WAS TAKEN TO A CLINIC FOR EVALUATION.  AFTER REVIEWING THE MSDS, IT CONFIRMED THAT THE CONTENTS MET THE DEFINITION OF A DANGEROUS GOOD EVEN THOUGH THE SHIPPER HAD NOT OFFERED THE MATERIAL AS SUCH.  THE CLINIC THEN NOTIFIED THE AIRPORT FIRE DEPARTMENT WHO RESPONDED TO THE FEDEX TERMINAL WITH HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM.  THE AIRPORT FIRE DEPARTMENT ALSO NOTIFIED THE FAA WHO INVESTIGATED THE SHIPMENT THE NEXT DAY.  THE FAA WAS NOT NOTIFIED THAT NIGHT BECAUSE THEY HAD BEEN NOTIFIED BY THE AIRPORT FIRE DEPT PRIOR TO CONFIRMATION THAT THE PACKAGE WAS A HIDDEN.

SULFURIC ACID WAS BEING TRANSFERRED FROM THE RAILCAR TO THE HOLDING TANK FOR APPROXIMATELY 3 HOURS, WHEN THE FLEX HOSE SPLIT ABOUT 6 TO 8 INCHES FROM WHERE IT CONNECTS TO THE RIGIS TRANSFER LINE.  RAILCAR WAS UNDER PRESSURE.  LESS THAN 1000 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID WAS LOST.  NO HAZARDOUS WASTE INVOLVED.

DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AT BULK PLANT.  HE DID NOT HAVE A TANK CHART AND WASN'T SURE OF THE SIZE OF THE TANK.  AFTER HE UNLOADED EACH COMPARTMENT HE WOULD CHECK THE TANK GAUGE.  WHEN HE GOT TO THE LAST COMPARTMENT HE THOUGHT IT WOULD HOLD IT ALL, BUT JUST AS THE COMPARTMENT WENT DRY THE TANK OVERFLOWED.  WE HAVE CONTACTED THE CUSTOMER TO OBTAIN A TANK CHART SO THAT THE DRIVER KNOWS THE SIZE OF THE TANK AND HOW MUCH IT WILL HOLD IN CASE HE IS AT THE LOCATION BY HIMSELF.

ON 4/01/95 AT APPROXIMATELY 0122 HOURS, THERE WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPILL IN BUILDING A OF OUR SORT FACILITY.  BUILDING A IS LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH  45177 WHICH IS ABX AIR, INC.  PRIMARY BUSINESS ADDRESS.  DUE TO THE ODOR/FUMES FROM THE LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  WE EVACUATED APPROXIMATELY 75 PEOPLE  FROM BUILDING A 25 OF THESE EMPLOYEES FILED ACCIDENT REPORTS DUE TO EXPERIENCING SYMPTOMS CAUSED FROM THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  4 OF THE 25 EMPLOYEES WERE TAKEN TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM OF THE LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR A PHYSICANS EVALUATION.  SEE ATTACHED FOR DETAILS OF THE SPILL CHRONOLOGY.  THE SHIPMENT WAS INSPECTED FURTHER AND THE FOLLOW NOTES WERE TAKEN OF THE DESCRIPTION FOR THE PURPOSE OF THIS REPORT:  THE OUTER PACKAGING WAS A HARD SHELL PLASTIC CAST THAT WAS SECURED CLOSED WITH BARLOCK TIES.  THERE WERE NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE OUTER PACKAGING, NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO ORIENTATION MARKINGS ON THE OUTER PACKAGING.  INSIDE THE PLASTIC CASE WE FOUND A BLUE FOAM MOLD WITH CUT SECTIONS TO ACCOMMODATE 3 x 1 QUART PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH SCREW-TYPE CLOSURES.  BOTTLES 1 OF 3 WAS LASER DYE. THIS BOTTLE WAS FULL AND UNDAMAGED.  BOTTLE 2 OF 3 WAS EMPTY AND NOT DAMAGED.  BOTTLES 3 OF 3 CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 6 OUNCES OF PRODUCT HAD AN NFDA RATING OF 1-0HEALTH, 3 FLAMMABILITY, 0-REACTIVITY, NO SPECIAL HANDLING NOTES.  THIS PRODUCT IS CALLED TRIPLET QUENCHER.  THE PLASTIC SCREW-TYPE CLOSURE WAS CRACKED ON THIS BOTTLE CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 26 OUNCES OF PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT.  THIS PRODUCT WAS SOURCES OF THE ODOR/FUMES WE EVACUATED BUILDING A FOR.  WE WERE UNABLE TO DETERMINE WHAT CAUSED THE DAMAGE TO THE PLASTIC CLOSURE.  ATTACHED TO THIS REPORT IS THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS THAT THE SHIPPER HAS PROVIDED.

column168: ON 4/5/95 AT 0117, SORT FACILITY LEAD, JAMES WILLIAM, REPORTED AN ODOR COMING FROM AN AREA IN SECONDARY EIGHT (8) SORT FACILITY BUILDING "B" UPSTAIRS. I, ADDIE CAMPTON, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COOR., AND P/T SPILL TECHNICIAN, DAVID JARRELL, RESPONDED. UPON OUR ARRIVAL, WE DISCOVERED A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS EMITTING AN ODOR AND WAS COMPLETELY SATURATED. WE FIRST DOCUMENTED ALL THE MARKINGS OF THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX. THIS SHIPMENT HAD PRE-PRINTED MARKINGS STATING THAT THIS WAS AN ORM-D AND THE PRODUCT WAS CALLED "BRAKE KLEEN". WE BEGAN OUR INVESTIGATION OF THE INNER CONTENTS. THE CONTENTS ARE AS FOLLOWS: 12 METAL AEROSOL RECEPTACLES, ONE OF WHICH HAD RUPTURED AT THE TOP OF THE RECEPTACLE AND ALL OF THE CONTENTS WERE LOST. THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING WOULD BE THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS POSSIBLY STRUCK OR CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT AND THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED NO ABSORBENT TO CONTAIN THE LEAKAGE. CLEAR OF SCENE AT 0152.

ON 4/4/95 A SPILL WAS REPORTED BY CERT O RHONDA CLONCH, A LEAD FOR THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT FACILITY. I, ADDIE CAMPTON, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORD., AND P/T SPILL TECHNICIAN, DAVID JARRELL RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL WE DISCOVERED A FIBREBOARD BOX LABELED CORROSIVE. THE BOX WAS DAMP ON ONE END. WE BEGAN OUR INVESTIGATION OF THE INNER CONTENTS. THE INNER CONTENTS ARE AS FOLLOWS: 4 1-GALLON PLASTIC RECEPTACLES, EACH CONTAINING A PRODUCT CALLED "RINSE ADDITIVE", WHICH HAD BEEN LABELED ON ALL 6 RECEPTACLES. THE RECEPTACLES HAD PLASTIC SCREW-TYPE CLOSURES, WHICH APPEARED TO BE LOOSE. THE PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WERE SEPARATED BY A FIBREBOARD DIVIDER AND THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINED NO ABSORBENT. THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX WAS A DOT 12B SPECIFICATION BOX WITH ORIENTATION LABELS AND A CORROSIVE LABEL. THIS SHIPMENT WAS THEN REPACKED WITH ABSORBENT AND CLOSURES SECURED. WE NEXT PLACED THIS SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS AND THEN IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND MOVED ON TO TO DESTINATION. THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING IS THAT THE SHIPMENT'S CLOSURES WERE NOT SECURED. CLEAR OF SCENE 0345.

THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED, BE INTACT.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. ON 040995 AT APPROXIMATELY 5PM REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM MTO MCCARTHY THAT A SWITCHMAN HAD DISCOVERED THE ABOVE HYDROCHLORIC ACID CAR LEAKING A PENCIL SIZE STREAM OUT THE SIDE OF THE CAR.  REEDER ASKED THAT THE CAR BE MOVED IMMEDIATELY TO A SAFE AREA FOR UNLOADING.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND ASKED FOR SHIPPER CONTACT.  REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM REAGENT CHEMICAL AT ABOUT 520PM.  THEY WERE ASKED TO SEND A RESPONSE TEAM AND TRUCKS FOR OFF LOADING THE CAR.  REEDER ALSO ASKED MCCARTHY TO CHECK FOR ANY EMPTY CARS IN THE YARD THAT LAST CONTAINED HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  THE HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM WAS NOTIFIED.  WORKING TOGETHER, THE LEAK WAS FINALLY SEALED.  THE CAR WAS UNLOADED INTO TRUCKS USING EQUIPMENT SUPPLIED BY REAGEANT.  AS ESTIMATED 150 GALS OF ACID WERE LOST.  ALL SPILLED ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED USING SODA ASH.  A PH TEST INDICATED ABOUT 7.5 IN THE AREA OF THE SPILL. column168: ON 4/7/95 AT 03:58AM SORT SUPERVISOR, DAN ECKLE REPORTED A THAT WAS LEAKING AND HAD AN ODOR.  HE ALSO ADVISED THAT HE INADVERTENTLY CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE PACKAGE.  HE FOLLOWED STANDARD COMPANY POLICY AND IMMEDIATELY WASHED HIS HANDS WITH WARM WATER AND LIQUID SOAP.  MR. ECKLE HAD ALREADY CONTACTED HAZMAT DISPATCH WHO IN TURN DISPATCHED A SPILL TEAM TO THE LOCATION OF THE LEAKING PACKAGE.  UPON ARRIVAL CERT 13.  JEFF MCLAUGHLIN OPENING THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION FOUND 24 PLASTIC BOTTLES EACH CONTAINING 16 OUNCES (473ML) OF ETHYL RUBBING ALCOHOL (70%).  FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE INNER CONTENTS REVEALED NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE PLASTIC SCREW TYPE CLOSURE CAUSING ONE INNER CONTAINER TO LOOSE ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS AND ANOTHER TO LOOSE APPROXIMATELY 1 OUNCE.  THE ABSENCE OF ABSORBENT/CUSHIONING MATERIAL AND THAT NONE OF THE INNER PLASTIC WAS USED WAS NOT LARGE ENOUGH FOR THEM BE PLACED IN AN UPRIGHT MANNER ACCORDING TO THE CLOSURES OF THE PACKAGE.  UPON VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE OUTER PACKAGE IT WAS NOTED THAT THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS TO INDICATE THAT THE PACKAGE CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS SHIPPED ON AN AIRBORNE EXPRESS LIBRA LABEL WHICH ALSO DID NOT INDICATE THAT A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS BEING SHIPPED.  THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO TWO PLASTIC BAGS TO CONTAIN THE LEAKING CONTENTS AND WAS PLACED IN OUR FLAMMABLE LIQUID CABINET UNDER LOCK AND KEY.  UPON RELEASE FROM THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION INSPECTORS, THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE REPACKED, MARKED AND LABELED ACCORDING TO ALL STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS AND UPON RECEIPT OF A SIGNED SHIPPERS CERTIFICATION FROM THE SHIPPER WILL BE FORWARDED OR RETURNED PER THE SHIPPERS REQUEST.  THE ABOVE STATEMENT IS TRUE AND ACCURATE TO THE BEST OF MY KNOWLEDGE SIGNATURE OF PERSON FILING REPORT.

TWO OF THE FIBREBOARD BOXES CONTAINED 3 TO 4 OTHER FIBERBOARD BOXES WITH GLASS VIALS CONTAINING RESIN SOLUTION.  ONE SMALLER FIBERBOARD BOX WAS OF A THINNER CARDBOARD AND IT ALSO CONTAINED A GLASS VIAL OF RESIN SOLUTION WHICH WAS EMITTING AN ODOR.  AFTER OPENING ONE OF THE FIBERBOARD BOXES, WE FOUND GLASS VIALS OF RESIN SOLUTION.  THERE APPEARED TO BE 2 VIALS THAT WERE BROKEN AND EMITTING AN ODOR.  THE SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND MOVED ON TO ITS DESTINATION. column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30 AM ON APRIL 20, 1995.  I RECEIVED A CALL FROM UHP DISPATCH, INFORMING ME THAT PT-6 HAD BROKEN LOOSE FROM THE MAIN TRAILER AND TIPPED OVER AND WAS LEAKING GAS.  I LEFT TREMONTON AT 9:30 AM WITH TRUCK #15 AND A DROP DECK, WITH TROY REDMOND IN TRUCK #5 BOBTAIL, TO PUMP THE GAS OFF THE WRECKED TRAILER AND LEE RASMUSSEN IN HIS OWN PERSONEL TRUCK. WE ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 12:15 PM AND WERE ESCORTED TO THE SIGHT OF THE ACCIDENT, AT MILE POST 202.  I MADE CONTACT WITH THE IUHP OFFICER IN CHARGE HE ASKED ME HOW MUCH GAS I THOUGHT WAS ON THE TRAILER AND FROM WHAT I HAD OBSERVED AT THAT TIME, IT WAS MY OPINION THAT THE TANK WAS PROBABLY STILL 70 TO 80 PERCENT FULL.  OFFICER AMES STATED THE TANK WAS CRACKED AND HE WOULD NOT LET US PUMP IT OFF.  THE OPTIONS WERE TO  VENT TO THE ATMOSPHERE, THE REMAINING GAS OR TWO MORE OPTIONS OF A HIGH RISK. THIS WENT ON FOR APPROXIMATELY ONE HOUR AT WHICH TIME WE HAD DECIDED THAT THE TANK HAD REFRIGERATED AND COULD NOT GET ANYMORE GAS THROUGH THE VAPOR VALVES,  SAM CLARK ARRIVED AT THIS TIME AND TOOK CHARGE AND SET UP THE FLARE TREE HE HAD BROUGHT ALONG.  WE THEN SPRAYED WATER ON THE TANK TO WARM IT, SO WE SOULD FINISH VENTING AS MUCH GAS AS POSSIBLE BEFORE THE UHP WOULD LET THE CRANE UPRIGHT THE TANK.  AT THIS TIME WE PUMPED OFF THE REST OF THE GAS AND FOUND THAT THE TANK WAS NOT CRACKED OR RUPTURED, BUT THE SPITTER GAUGE HAD BEEN DAMAGED AND WAS LEAKING.  THE GAS WAS COMPRESSED ONTO TRUCK #5 AND THE CRANE LOADED PT-6 ONTO DROP DECK AND REMOVED TO A SAFE LOCATION TO FINISH REMOVING THE SPITTER GAUGE FROM THE TRAILER, SO WE COULD PLUG THE HOLE AND BRING THE TRAILER TO TREMONTON, UTAH.

ON THE INSIDE WERE TWO INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES EACH CONTAINING A GLASS RECEPTACLE OF A FLAMMABLE LIQUID "ACETYL METYL CARBINOL", "UN2621".  AN INSPECTION OF THE GLASS RECEPTACLES WE FOUND THAT BOTH HAD THE BOTTOMS BROKEN ALL OF THE CONTENTS WAS LOST, WHICH WAS APPROXIMAELY .500L OF PRODUCT.  THE CONTENTS OF THE RECEPTACLES HAD BEEN ABSORBED BY THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  THE BOX WAS THEN REPACKED IN A RECOVERY DRUM DUE TO THE ODOR.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THE BOX.  THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR FAILURE OF THIS BOX WAS THE INNER BOX DID NOT CONTAIN ENOUGH CUSHIONING MATERIAL TO WITHSTAND A FOUR (4) FOTT DROP TEST.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0150.

column168: AFTER LEAVING THE QUANTUM FACILITY, THE TRUCK APPROACHED A RAILROAD CROSSING; THE DRIVER APPLIED THE BREAKS ON THE APPROACH AND GOING OVER THE TRACKS THE DRIVER NOTED A RELEASE FROM HIS TRUCK; HE IMMEDIATELY STOPPED AND INVESTIGATED THE SITUATION; HIS INSPECTION REVEALED THE FRONT TOP CLOSURE ON THE TANK TRAILER HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY SECURED; THIS ALLOWED THE MATERIAL TO ESCAPE AFTER THE BREAKING HAD CAUSED THE MATERIAL TO MOVE FORWARD AND SLOUGHS OUT THE TOP OPENING; THE MATERIAL THEN RAN OFF THE SIDE OF THE TANKER AND ON TO THE PAVEMENT BELOW. THE DRIVER SECURED THE AREA AND CALLED FOR HELP IMMEDIATELY. AMS PERSONNEL ARRIVED SHORTLY THERE AFTER AND BEGAN CLEANUP BY FIRST NEUTRALIZING THE MATERIAL WITH SODA ASH AND THEN ABSORBING ALL LIQUIDS WITH SAND; THE MATERIALS WERE THEN PICKED UP USING A BOBCAT TYPE FRONT END LOADER AND SHOVELS AND BROOM; ALL MATERIALS WERE PLACED IN TO A 25 YARD ROLL OFF BIN SPOTTED ON SITE. THE TOTAL CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETELY BY APPROXIMATELY 17:30 OF THIS SAME DAY. THE ROLL OFF BIN WAS MOVED TO THE MCS YARD IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING COMPLETION OF THE CLEAN UP ACTIVITIES. A SAMPLE OF THE MATERIAL PICKED UP WAS DELIVERED TO SAYBOLT LAB FOR ANALYSIS TO CONFIRM IF THE MATERIAL WAS A HAZARDOUS WASTE. THE SUBSEQUENT ANALYSIS, REPORT #E9504.737 DATED APRIL 28, 1995, INDICATED THE MATERIAL WAS IN FACT NOT REGULATED BY RCRA, AND WAS THEREFORE APPROPRIATE FOR LANDFILL AT A CLASS 1 FACILITY. A WASTE CODE WAS ISSUED BY THE TNRCCAS SPIL3011; THE MATERIAL WAS PROFILED, APPROVED, AND LANDFILLED AT THE WESTERN WASTE INDUSTRIES FACILITY IN CONROE, TEXAS. THE MATERIAL WAS MOVED ON TNRCC MANIFEST NUMBER 00808963 ON MAY 4, 1995.
